## 3. Phase 1 — Fundamentals (Weeks 1–3) <a name="phase-1"></a>

### Week 1 — Networking & Communication Basics

#### ✅ 1.1 OSI Model & TCP/IP

- OSI 7 layers (Physical → Application)
- TCP vs UDP — when to use each
- HTTP/1.1 vs HTTP/2 vs HTTP/3 (QUIC)
- HTTPS, TLS handshake

**Key Interview Points:**
- TCP: reliable, ordered, connection-oriented → use for APIs, file transfers
- UDP: unreliable, fast, connectionless → use for video streaming, DNS, gaming
- HTTP/2: multiplexing over single connection, header compression, server push
- HTTP/3: built on QUIC (UDP-based), eliminates head-of-line blocking

#### ✅ 1.2 DNS (Domain Name System)

- DNS resolution chain: Client → Recursive Resolver → Root → TLD → Authoritative
- Record types: A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, TXT, NS
- TTL and caching implications
- DNS-based load balancing

**Key Interview Points:**
- DNS is the first hop in every web request — understand its latency impact
- Low TTL = more DNS lookups = flexible but slower; High TTL = cached = faster
- GeoDNS routes users to nearest data center

#### ✅ 1.3 APIs

- REST vs GraphQL vs gRPC vs WebSockets
- REST principles: stateless, uniform interface, resource-based
- gRPC: Protocol Buffers, streaming, low latency (use for internal microservices)
- GraphQL: flexible queries, no over/under-fetching (use for complex client needs)
- WebSockets: full-duplex persistent connection (use for real-time chat, live feeds)

**Comparison Table:**

| Protocol | Format | Use Case | Latency |
|---|---|---|---|
| REST | JSON/XML | Public APIs, CRUD | Medium |
| gRPC | Protobuf | Internal services | Low |
| GraphQL | JSON | Complex queries | Medium |
| WebSocket | Binary/JSON | Real-time | Very Low |
| SSE | Text | Server push only | Low |

