### Week 3 — Scalability Concepts

#### ✅ 3.1 Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling

| | Vertical (Scale Up) | Horizontal (Scale Out) |
|---|---|---|
| How | Bigger machine | More machines |
| Limit | Hardware cap | Virtually unlimited |
| Cost | Exponential | Linear |
| Complexity | Low | High (distributed) |
| Failure | Single point | Fault tolerant |

#### ✅ 3.2 Latency Numbers Every Engineer Should Know

```
L1 cache reference:           0.5 ns
L2 cache reference:           7 ns
Main memory reference:        100 ns
SSD random read:              16 µs (16,000 ns)
HDD random read:              2 ms  (2,000,000 ns)
Send 1K bytes over 1Gbps:     10 µs
Round trip in same datacenter: 500 µs
Round trip across US:         150 ms
Round trip across world:      300 ms
```

> **Tip:** Memorize these orders of magnitude. They justify architectural decisions.

#### ✅ 3.3 Back-of-Envelope Estimation

**Key Numbers:**
- 1 million seconds ≈ 11.5 days
- 1 day = 86,400 seconds ≈ 100K seconds
- 1 byte = 8 bits
- 1 KB = 10³ bytes, 1 MB = 10⁶, 1 GB = 10⁹, 1 TB = 10¹², 1 PB = 10¹⁵

**Example — Twitter Scale:**
- 300M users, 50% DAU = 150M DAU
- Each user posts 2 tweets/day → 300M tweets/day → 3,500 tweets/second (write QPS)
- Each user reads 100 tweets/day → 15B reads/day → 175,000 reads/second (read QPS)
- Read:Write ratio ≈ 50:1 → read-heavy → optimize for reads with caching

