## 4. Phase 2 — Core Building Blocks (Weeks 4–6) <a name="phase-2"></a>

### Week 4 — Load Balancing, Caching, CDN

#### ✅ 4.1 Load Balancers

**Types:**
- Layer 4 (Transport): Routes based on IP/port, fast, no content inspection (e.g., AWS NLB)
- Layer 7 (Application): Routes based on URL, headers, cookies — smart routing (e.g., AWS ALB, Nginx)

**Algorithms:**

| Algorithm | How It Works | Best For |
|---|---|---|
| Round Robin | Each server in turn | Uniform load, stateless |
| Weighted Round Robin | Based on server capacity | Heterogeneous servers |
| Least Connections | Server with fewest active connections | Long-lived connections |
| IP Hash | Hash of client IP → consistent server | Session stickiness |
| Random | Pick random server | Simple, uniform |

**Key Concepts:**
- **Health checks:** Periodically ping servers; remove unhealthy ones
- **Session stickiness (Affinity):** Route same user to same server — avoid when possible (stateless is better)
- **Hot Standby:** Passive failover vs Active-Active (both serving)

#### ✅ 4.2 Caching

**Cache Hit vs Miss:**
- Cache Hit: data found in cache → fast response
- Cache Miss: data not found → fetch from DB, write to cache → slower first time

**Caching Strategies:**

| Strategy | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| Cache-Aside (Lazy) | App checks cache; on miss, reads DB and populates cache | Resilient to cache failure | Cache miss on first read, stale data possible |
| Write-Through | Write to cache AND DB simultaneously | Always consistent | Higher write latency |
| Write-Behind (Write-Back) | Write to cache; async write to DB | Low write latency | Risk of data loss |
| Refresh-Ahead | Proactively refresh cache before expiry | Low latency | Wasted resources if not accessed |

**Cache Eviction Policies:**
- **LRU (Least Recently Used):** Evict items not accessed recently — most common
- **LFU (Least Frequently Used):** Evict items accessed least often
- **FIFO:** Evict oldest item regardless of access
- **TTL-based:** Expire after time limit

**What to Cache:**
- Database query results
- Computed/aggregated results
- Session data
- API responses (rate-limited external APIs)
- HTML fragments

**What NOT to Cache:**
- Frequently changing data
- Financial data requiring strong consistency
- Per-user private data without proper isolation

**Redis vs Memcached:**

| | Redis | Memcached |
|---|---|---|
| Data structures | Rich (lists, sets, sorted sets, hashes) | Simple key-value only |
| Persistence | Yes (RDB, AOF) | No |
| Replication | Yes | No |
| Clustering | Yes | Limited |
| Pub/Sub | Yes | No |
| Use case | General caching, queues, leaderboards | Pure high-speed caching |

#### ✅ 4.3 Content Delivery Networks (CDN)

- **What:** Geographically distributed edge servers caching static content
- **Purpose:** Reduce latency by serving content from server closest to user
- **Works for:** Images, CSS, JS, videos, static HTML

**CDN Types:**
- **Pull CDN:** Origin server is source of truth; CDN fetches on first miss (lazy), TTL controls freshness
- **Push CDN:** You proactively push content to CDN; good for large files, less dynamic

**Cache Invalidation:**
- Versioned URLs: `app.v2.3.js` — change filename on deploy
- Purge API: Explicitly invalidate CDN cache on deploy
- Short TTL: Risky (more origin hits), but ensures freshness

**Popular CDNs:** Cloudflare, AWS CloudFront, Fastly, Akamai

