### Week 5 — Message Queues & Asynchronous Processing

#### ✅ 5.1 Why Message Queues?

**Problems they solve:**
- Decouples producers from consumers
- Handles traffic spikes (queue buffers load)
- Enables async processing (email, notifications, image processing)
- Retry failed operations
- Fan-out to multiple consumers

#### ✅ 5.2 Message Queue Patterns

**Point-to-Point (Queue):**
- One producer, one consumer per message
- Message is consumed and deleted
- Use: Task queues, job processing
- Example: AWS SQS

**Publish-Subscribe (Topic):**
- One producer, many consumers
- Each subscriber gets every message
- Use: Notifications, event broadcasting
- Example: AWS SNS, Redis Pub/Sub

**Competing Consumers:**
- Multiple consumers read from same queue
- Each message processed by exactly ONE consumer
- Use: Worker pools, parallel processing

#### ✅ 5.3 Kafka Deep Dive

**Core Concepts:**

```
Producer → [Topic (Partitions 0,1,2)] → Consumer Group
                    ↑
                 Broker Cluster
                 (ZooKeeper / KRaft)
```

- **Topic:** Logical channel for messages
- **Partition:** Ordered, immutable log within a topic (unit of parallelism)
- **Offset:** Position of a message in a partition
- **Consumer Group:** Group of consumers sharing work; each partition → one consumer
- **Broker:** Kafka server hosting partitions
- **Replication Factor:** Number of copies of each partition across brokers

**Key Properties:**
- Ordered within a partition (NOT across partitions)
- Messages retained for configurable period (e.g., 7 days) — re-consumable
- At-least-once delivery by default; exactly-once with idempotent producers

**Kafka vs RabbitMQ:**

| | Kafka | RabbitMQ |
|---|---|---|
| Model | Distributed log | Traditional message broker |
| Throughput | Millions/sec | Thousands/sec |
| Message retention | Configurable (days) | Consumed and deleted |
| Ordering | Per-partition | Per-queue |
| Use case | Event streaming, log aggregation | Task queues, RPC |
| Consumer model | Pull | Push |

