## 5. Phase 3 — Distributed Systems Deep Dive (Weeks 7–9) <a name="phase-3"></a>

### Week 7 — Consistency, Availability & Fault Tolerance

#### ✅ 7.1 Consistency Models

**Strong Consistency:**
- Every read sees the most recent write
- All nodes see the same data at the same time
- Example: single-node DB, Zookeeper, etcd
- Cost: Higher latency, lower availability

**Eventual Consistency:**
- Given no new updates, all nodes will eventually converge
- Reads may return stale data temporarily
- Example: DNS, Cassandra, DynamoDB
- Cost: Application must handle stale reads

**Read-Your-Own-Writes:**
- After a write, the same user sees their write on subsequent reads
- Even if globally eventual — your session sees your data

**Monotonic Reads:**
- If you read version X, you'll never see an older version again
- Implemented via sticky reads (same replica) or version tracking

**Causal Consistency:**
- Operations causally related are seen in the right order by all processes
- Stronger than eventual, weaker than strong

#### ✅ 7.2 Distributed Transactions

**Two-Phase Commit (2PC):**
```
Phase 1 (Prepare):  Coordinator → asks all participants "Can you commit?"
                    All participants: "Yes" (lock resources) or "No"
Phase 2 (Commit):   If ALL said yes → Coordinator sends Commit
                    If ANY said no → Coordinator sends Abort
```
- Problem: Coordinator failure in Phase 2 → participants blocked (holding locks)
- Problem: Blocking protocol — not suitable for microservices

**Saga Pattern (Preferred for Microservices):**
- Long-running transaction split into local transactions
- Each local transaction publishes event/message
- On failure: compensating transactions (undo)

```
Order Service → Payment Service → Inventory Service → Shipping Service
      ↓(fail)       ↓(rollback)      ↓(rollback)       ↓(rollback)
Cancel Order  ← Refund Payment ← Restore Inventory ← Cancel Shipment
```

**Saga Implementations:**
- **Choreography:** Each service reacts to events (no central coordinator) — simpler, hard to track
- **Orchestration:** Central orchestrator tells services what to do — complex but easier to monitor

#### ✅ 7.3 Leader Election

**Why:** Distributed systems need coordination — one node must be authoritative for writes

**Algorithms:**
- **Bully Algorithm:** Highest ID node becomes leader; sends "I'm the boss" messages
- **Raft:** Leader elected by majority vote; log replication ensures consistency
- **Paxos:** Classic consensus algorithm; complex but provably correct

**Tools that handle this for you:**
- Apache ZooKeeper: ephemeral znodes for leadership
- etcd: used by Kubernetes for leader election
- Redis SETNX: simple but less robust

#### ✅ 7.4 Failure Detection

**Heartbeat:** Periodic health signals; if no heartbeat → suspected failure

**Gossip Protocol:**
- Nodes periodically share state with random peers
- State propagates across cluster exponentially
- Decentralized, scalable, no single point of failure
- Used by: Cassandra, DynamoDB

**Phi Accrual Failure Detector:**
- Adaptive failure detection based on heartbeat history
- Returns a failure probability (φ value) rather than binary fail/not-fail
- Used by Cassandra

