### Week 9 — Search, Analytics & Real-Time Systems

#### ✅ 9.1 Full-Text Search (Elasticsearch)

**Architecture:**
- Index = collection of documents (like a DB table)
- Shard = unit of storage (Lucene index)
- Replica = copy of shard for HA and read scaling

**How it works:**
1. Document ingested → analyzed → inverted index created
2. Query → analyzed → matched against inverted index
3. Relevance scored (BM25 algorithm by default)

**Inverted Index:**
```
Word "payment" → [doc1, doc5, doc23]
Word "failed"  → [doc2, doc5, doc18]
Search: "payment failed" → intersect → [doc5]
```

**Common Use Cases:**
- Product search (e-commerce)
- Log aggregation and analysis (ELK stack)
- Auto-complete suggestions
- Full-text content search

**Sync DB → Elasticsearch:**
- Dual writes (risky — partial failure)
- CDC (Change Data Capture): Debezium reads DB binlog → Kafka → Elasticsearch
- Periodic batch sync (acceptable staleness)

#### ✅ 9.2 Time-Series Databases

- Optimized for append-only, time-ordered data
- Efficient compression for repeated values
- Automatic data downsampling (high-res → low-res over time)
- Examples: InfluxDB, TimescaleDB, Prometheus, OpenTSDB

**Use Cases:** Metrics, monitoring, IoT sensor data, financial ticks

#### ✅ 9.3 Data Warehouses vs Data Lakes

| | Data Warehouse | Data Lake |
|---|---|---|
| Data | Structured, processed | Raw, any format |
| Schema | Schema-on-write | Schema-on-read |
| Purpose | BI, reporting | Data science, ML |
| Examples | Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift | S3 + Athena, Delta Lake |
| Performance | Fast queries | Slower, flexible |

**Lambda Architecture:**
```
New Data → Batch Layer (historical) + Speed Layer (real-time)
                                ↓
                         Serving Layer (merged view)
```

**Kappa Architecture:**
- Stream everything through one layer (Kafka-based)
- Simpler than Lambda, but requires reprocessing for historical data

