## 6. Phase 4 — Real-World System Design (Weeks 10–12) <a name="phase-4"></a>

### Week 10 — Design Social & Communication Systems

#### ✅ 10.1 Design a Chat System (WhatsApp/Slack)

**Requirements:**
- 1-1 and group messaging
- Online/offline status
- Message delivery (sent, delivered, read receipts)
- Push notifications for offline users

**Key Design Decisions:**

```
Client ←[WebSocket]→ Chat Server ←→ Message Queue (Kafka)
                          ↓
                   Message DB (Cassandra)
                          ↓
                   Notification Service → APNs/FCM
```

- **Why WebSocket:** Persistent connection; server can push messages to client
- **Why Cassandra:** High write throughput, time-series message storage, wide-column suits `(user_id, time)` queries
- **Message fan-out (group chat):** Write to each member's inbox OR use pull model
- **Online presence:** Redis pub/sub + heartbeat; expire key after 30s

**Message ID Design:**
- Use Snowflake IDs (timestamp + machine ID + sequence) for global ordering within user's messages

#### ✅ 10.2 Design a News Feed (Facebook/Twitter)

**Push (Fan-out on write):**
- When user posts → immediately write to all followers' feeds
- Pro: Fast feed reads (pre-computed)
- Con: Celebrity with 10M followers → 10M writes per post (write amplification)

**Pull (Fan-out on read):**
- When user opens feed → fetch posts from all followed accounts and merge
- Pro: No write amplification
- Con: Slow feed reads (especially with many followees)

**Hybrid Approach (Twitter's actual approach):**
- Regular users: Push model
- Celebrities (>1M followers): Pull model on read
- Feed read = pre-computed feed + real-time pull from celebrities → merge

**Feed Ranking:**
- Simple: Chronological
- Smart: ML model scoring (engagement probability, recency, user affinity)

